Of a pentagon, a hexagon, and a heptagon, of the same side length, which one covers the maximum area inside it?  Of course, among these three figures, which is the regular one? Clearly, a regular pentagon! And a regular hexagon! And a regular heptagon!
Recall that the side length of a regular $n-$gon inscribed in a circle is given by $d\sin\frac{180}{n},$ where $d$ is the diameter of the circle. And  it is well-known that $\sin\frac{180}{n}$ is a decreasing function of $n.$ So, that implies a regular heptagon will cover the larger such a shape.

So let this heptagon be a pizza, paste a slice of this pizza along a diagonal of the hexagon, cake comes in the shape of a trapezoid, and one cake to the right of the other -- these two shapes are stacked such that they form a parallelogram! :)

Clearly, one cake will cover half the area of the trapezoid! Now, as both the base of the trapezoid are equal, so it becomes a special case. So the trapezoid will be in the shape of a rectangle. Then the length of the rectangular cake will be $\frac{d}{2}\left(\sin\frac{360}{7}+\sin\frac{360}{7}\right)=d\sin\frac{360}{7}.$ And the width is $\frac{d}{2}\sin\frac{180}{6}=\frac{d}{4}.$
So, the area to be covered by the trapezoid is $\frac{1}{2}\times d\sin\frac{180}{7}\times d\sin\frac{360}{7}=\frac{d^2}{2}\sin\frac{720}{9}=\frac{d^2}{2}\sin 80.$

So we have the area of the overlapping region as $\frac{1}{14}\times\frac{d^2}{2}\sin 80=\frac{1}{28}d^2\sin 80.$ Similarly another overlapping region will be $\frac{1}{28}d^2\sin 100.$ And the overlapping common region will resemble the both the regions.

So we subtract the area of these two regions from a rectangle with sides $\frac{d}{4}$ and $\frac{d}{2}\left(\sin\frac{360}{7}+\sin\frac{360}{7}\right).$ So the final area will be:
$\left(\frac{3d}{4}\right)^2-\left(\frac{d}{4}\right)^2\sin 80-\left(\frac{d}{4}\right)^2\sin 100=\frac{9d^2}{16}-\sin 100\times\frac{d^2}{16}=\frac{1}{17}-\sin 100.$ So $d^2=\frac{16}{17}\left(1-\sin 100\right).$


